$\begin{align}
\dfrac{x^2+3x+2}{x+1} &= \dfrac{\cancel{(x+1)}(x+2)}{\cancel{x+1}}
\\\\
&=x+2
\end{align}$

We did it! We can apply the power rule to every term in $x+2$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{x^2+7x+12}{x+3} &= \dfrac{\cancel{(x+3)}(x+4)}{\cancel{x+3}}
\\\\
&=x+4
\end{align}$

We did it! We can apply the power rule to every term in $x+4$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{x^2-3x-40}{x-8} &= \dfrac{\cancel{(x-8)}(x+5)}{\cancel{x-8}}
\\\\
&=x+5
\end{align}$

We did it! We can apply the power rule to every term in $x+5$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{x^2-x-42}{x+6} &= \dfrac{\cancel{(x+6)}(x-7)}{\cancel{x+6}}
\\\\
&=x-7
\end{align}$

We did it! We can apply the power rule to every term in $x-7$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{5x^3-x}{x} &= \dfrac{\cancel{x}(5x^2-1)}{\cancel{x}}
\\\\
&=5x^2-1
\end{align}$

We did it! We can apply the power rule to every term in $5x^2-1$.
